      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Construct stiffness QoI comparison — pooled N=11 across Lab 1 and Lab 2",
      "description": "FEA-predicted construct stiffness (N/mm) was compared against pooled experimental measurements from eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories following ASTM F1717. The FEA ensemble mean stiffness deviated from the experimental mean by 4.2% (Lab 1: 3.8%, Lab 2: 4.7%), well within the pre-established 10% acceptance threshold. The normalised error metric E/uval was computed as 0.81, satisfying the E/uval < 1.96 criterion. Experimental testing was conducted by the DePuy Synthes biomechanics laboratory (Lab 1, n=6) and an independent contract research organisation (Lab 2, n=5) between March and June 2023. Actuator displacement was applied at 5 mm/min under displacement control; load cell and displacement transducer calibrations were verified against NIST-traceable standards within 12 months of testing. FEA boundary conditions replicated the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry using rigid body elements at the superior and inferior block attachment points. Material properties for the Ti-6Al-4V screw were assigned from coupon tensile data (mean E = 114.2 GPa, σ_y = 896 MPa). Mesh convergence was confirmed at element size 0.35 mm with <1.5% change in peak von Mises stress. This result constitutes the primary quantitative validation evidence supporting the credibility claim.",
